News24 Africa on Twitter and Facebook. Weilin said the report published last week on the eve of the summit "will undermine the image of the newspaper" but not the relationship between China and Africa. The AU leadership did not address the report in their opening remarks on Sunday, and Ethiopian Prime Minister Hailemariam Desalegn downplayed Le Monde's findings. "There is nothing to be spied (on). I don't believe it," he told journalists. Le Monde says the AU's servers were changed and its IT systems redone after the copying was found. The newspaper also reports Ethiopian cyber security experts removed microphones hidden in the desks and walls of the headquarters. China is deeply invested in Africa, regularly offering low-interest loans and gifts to individual nations and doing $149.2 billion in trade with the continent in 2016. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  